(5290, 'Marriage and the Movies: A History', 'The topic of marriage in the movies has always provided a fascinating reflection of changing social attitudes, shifting morals and gender roles. We will explore how films have defined marriage, identified seven core problems, and varied its three narrative components -- a couple, their problems, their situation -- from decade to decade from the silent to the modern era.', 'The topic of marriage in the movies has always provided a fascinating reflection of changing social attitudes, shifting morals and gender roles. We will explore how films have defined marriage, identified seven core problems, and varied its three narrative components -- a couple, their problems, their situation -- from decade to decade from the silent to the modern era.', 'https://class.coursera.org/marriageandmovies-002/', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=52O2S7rPvtg', '2015-05-18', 5, 'https://coursera-course-photos.s3.amazonaws.com/2e/8d3700965511e3878ae16390f75cc9/marriage_logo.jpg', 'Humanities ,Music, Film, and Audio,', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'no', 'Wesleyan University,', '2015-11-18 00:00:00'),
(5291, 'Configuring the World: A Critical Political Economy Approach', 'In today’s world, politics and economics are inextricably interconnected, but what is the nature of this connectivity? What are the power relationships that shape the world economy today and create new challenges for international institutions facing globalization? What makes some countries wealthier than others? Do we face cultural diversity or fragmentation? Does the type of governance effect economic development and social change or is it the other way around? How do we measure it and how trustworthy is the data?  These issues and many more will be examined in this course along with up-to-date sources and biting criticism.   ', 'In today’s world, politics and economics are inextricably interconnected, but what is the nature of this connectivity? What are the power relationships that shape the world economy today and create new challenges for international institutions facing globalization? What makes some countries wealthier than others? Do we face cultural diversity or fragmentation? Does the type of governance effect economic development and social change or is it the other way around? How do we measure it and how trustworthy is the data?  These issues and many more will be examined in this course along with up-to-date sources and biting criticism.   ', 'https://class.coursera.org/configuringworld-004/', 'https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=myebt9G2REs', '2015-09-14', 8, 'https://coursera-course-photos.s3.amazonaws.com/46/7c25052d7779126610c2c81f409aaa/ConfWorldLogo.jpg', 'Economics & Finance,Humanities ,Social Sciences,', 'Coursera', 0, 'English', 'no', 'Universiteit Leiden,University of Geneva,', '2015-11-18 00:00:00'),
